WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.360
Last summer, I had the chance to participate in the writing of this book, which is called

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:19.040
R Markdown The Definitive Guide, and it's available for free online at this web address.

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:22.920
I'm particularly pleased to be involved with this project because I believe that history

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:27.780
will see R Markdown as a turning point in the replication crisis.

00:00:27.780 --> 00:00:32.520
If you haven't realized it yet, the replication crisis is the one dark cloud in the otherwise

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:36.619
bright future of data science, and it's a darker cloud than you might think.

00:00:36.619 --> 00:00:40.700
I'll assume that you may have heard something about the replication crisis because it's

00:00:40.700 --> 00:00:45.200
been widely reported on in academic journals like Nature, but also it's crossed over

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:49.500
into the mainstream, being published in papers like the Wall Street Journal and the New York

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:50.500
Times.

00:00:50.500 --> 00:00:56.060
Basically, earlier this decade, pharmaceutical companies noticed something alarming.

00:00:56.060 --> 00:01:00.500
As part of their work, pharmaceutical companies replicate the results of promising studies

00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:04.900
to evaluate whether or not they could turn the findings into a drug or a treatment that

00:01:04.900 --> 00:01:06.220
they could then sell.

00:01:06.220 --> 00:01:10.820
Normally, they keep what they find in-house because it's a competitive advantage, but

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:15.900
in 2012, the Amgen company noticed a picture that was so disturbing, they decided to make

00:01:15.900 --> 00:01:17.980
it public.

00:01:17.980 --> 00:01:21.660
Amgen had replicated the results of 53 landmark studies.

00:01:22.180 --> 00:01:26.220
Now, landmark is Amgen's word, but by that I mean studies that are influential and that

00:01:26.220 --> 00:01:28.620
other studies relied on.

00:01:28.620 --> 00:01:34.779
What Amgen discovered is they could only get the same results as six of the 53 studies.

00:01:34.779 --> 00:01:36.980
Now, that's really bad.

00:01:36.980 --> 00:01:40.699
In scientific terms, that means the other 47 studies might as well be wrong.

00:01:40.699 --> 00:01:45.220
In fact, they probably were wrong, but they were published in peer-reviewed journals and

00:01:45.220 --> 00:01:48.099
they're accepted as true by academia.

00:01:48.099 --> 00:01:52.260
After this announcement, the Bayer Pharmaceutical Company confirmed that they could only replicate

00:01:52.260 --> 00:01:57.459
the results of about 25% of the studies that they recreate.

00:01:57.459 --> 00:02:04.099
Since then, we've studied this in depth and our best estimate is that about 75% to 90%

00:02:04.099 --> 00:02:08.779
of research in preclinical studies is irreplicable.

00:02:08.779 --> 00:02:11.100
That means, again, that this research might be wrong.

00:02:11.100 --> 00:02:16.020
The results are likely coincidence at best.

00:02:16.020 --> 00:02:21.380
This should be concerning to you.

00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:25.259
Not only are academic reputations at stake, but there's a lot of money that is wasted

00:02:25.259 --> 00:02:27.740
on this research that can't be replicated.

00:02:27.740 --> 00:02:32.020
In fact, we have a very good estimate of how much money is wasted on irreplicable research

00:02:32.020 --> 00:02:36.580
in biomedicine, and that is $28 billion per year in the United States.

00:02:36.580 --> 00:02:42.940
Now, to put that in perspective, with $28 billion, you could buy a latte for everyone

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:46.300
on the planet from Starbucks.

00:02:46.300 --> 00:02:51.220
Now, if you're like me, you might not have a good sense of how many people are on the

00:02:51.220 --> 00:02:57.020
planet, but estimating based on the number of people in this room, with $28 billion,

00:02:57.020 --> 00:03:02.979
you could buy everybody in this room their own private island in the Bahamas, assuming

00:03:02.979 --> 00:03:06.699
that supplies last.

00:03:06.699 --> 00:03:12.380
This is just for research done in one year, and it's just money wasted in the United States,

00:03:12.380 --> 00:03:15.460
and it's just money wasted in the field of biomedicine.

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:19.979
Unfortunately, all signs suggest that the replication crisis is occurring across every

00:03:19.979 --> 00:03:22.020
branch of science.

00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:28.419
For example, a study of 18 influential economics articles from prestigious journals revealed

00:03:28.419 --> 00:03:32.300
that only six of them had results that could be replicated.

00:03:32.300 --> 00:03:37.580
A study of 21 articles from Nature and Science showed that only 13 of those articles had

00:03:37.580 --> 00:03:39.300
results that could be replicated.

00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:44.100
Now, Nature and Science are considered the most prestigious academic journals, and they

00:03:44.100 --> 00:03:46.940
publish work across all the domains of science.

00:03:46.940 --> 00:03:53.339
So while 13 out of 21 isn't technically half bad, it's still very alarming.

00:03:53.339 --> 00:03:54.699
And there's other reasons to be alarmed, too.

00:03:54.699 --> 00:03:59.500
We've seen that money is being wasted, but there's a real opportunity cost here.

00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:03.500
These studies are meant to do things like generate wealth, heal the environment, and

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:09.100
cure cancer, but they can't do that, and worse, they're misleading the people who would

00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:12.300
otherwise be solving those problems.

00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:17.980
I like a healthy environment, and I really do want them to cure cancer, especially before

00:04:17.980 --> 00:04:19.899
I get too old.

00:04:19.899 --> 00:04:24.540
The other thing is, these studies have become part of the scientific consensus, even though

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:28.339
they're useless, and we don't know which part of the consensus they are.

00:04:28.339 --> 00:04:31.779
I mean, yes, we do know the ones that were studied, but everything we haven't looked

00:04:31.779 --> 00:04:36.700
at, we don't know what's true and what's false.

00:04:36.700 --> 00:04:41.059
But more personally, if your expertise is closely associated with data science, and

00:04:41.059 --> 00:04:46.420
I suspect that it is since you're here, the replication crisis for you is a credibility

00:04:46.420 --> 00:04:47.940
crisis.

00:04:47.940 --> 00:04:52.779
The common denominator of all these studies is that they rely heavily on data and methods

00:04:52.779 --> 00:04:55.220
for analyzing data.

00:04:55.220 --> 00:04:58.980
And like it or not, commenters have observed this pattern.

00:04:58.980 --> 00:05:03.059
Academics, and presumably the people who read the New York Times and Wall Street Journal,

00:05:03.059 --> 00:05:07.540
are starting to realize that data is not a panacea, and neither are sophisticated methods

00:05:07.540 --> 00:05:10.739
for analyzing the data.

00:05:10.739 --> 00:05:16.619
You can solve this problem, but you need to spot the cause first.

00:05:16.619 --> 00:05:20.579
I can tell you what academia thinks is the cause, because the American Statistical Association

00:05:20.579 --> 00:05:22.739
published an article on it last fall.

00:05:22.739 --> 00:05:25.779
It's right here next to the cover story on R, which, by the way, is also a very good

00:05:25.779 --> 00:05:30.760
read, and the ASA used the metaphor of a cargo cult to explain what's going on.

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:32.940
So do you know what a cargo cult is?

00:05:32.940 --> 00:05:39.540
In World War II, after World War II, in isolated South Pacific islands, cargo cults developed.

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:43.679
During the war, natives who lived on these islands saw soldiers arrive and build airfields

00:05:43.679 --> 00:05:48.140
and radio towers and whatnot, and then miraculously, from the natives' perspective, planes descended

00:05:48.140 --> 00:05:52.179
from the sky, laden with cargo for the war effort, and a lot of that cargo made its way

00:05:52.179 --> 00:05:55.260
into the hands of the natives, who found it very, very useful.

00:05:55.260 --> 00:05:57.579
But the war ended, and the planes stopped coming.

00:05:57.579 --> 00:06:04.000
So in some places, the natives reconstructed landing fields, radio towers, radar dishes,

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.420
the things that they had seen the soldiers use to try to summon the planes back.

00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:11.140
They didn't understand the original technology, but they assumed if they did something that

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:13.980
looked similar, they could get similar results.

00:06:13.980 --> 00:06:15.459
Well that's the metaphor the ASA uses.

00:06:15.459 --> 00:06:20.420
The ASA says that many applications of statistics are cargo cult statistics.

00:06:20.420 --> 00:06:23.459
Practitioners go through the motions with scant understanding.

00:06:23.459 --> 00:06:26.959
In other words, the people analyzing data just don't know what they're doing.

00:06:26.959 --> 00:06:28.839
It's a convincing story in some ways.

00:06:28.839 --> 00:06:30.799
I'll show you.

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:33.679
This is a worked example for research workers.

00:06:33.679 --> 00:06:37.600
We can assume that Sir Ronald Fisher understood the original technology of statistics because

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:39.239
he invented most of it.

00:06:39.239 --> 00:06:43.480
The example begins here in blue text and continues for a few pages, and what Ronald Fisher is

00:06:43.480 --> 00:06:46.720
doing is he's stating his problem very precisely.

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:49.839
He's describing what he thinks are important characteristics of the problem.

00:06:49.839 --> 00:06:53.279
He's spotting some reasonable assumptions, and then he's inventing a method that can

00:06:53.279 --> 00:06:55.519
help him answer his question.

00:06:55.519 --> 00:06:57.200
And down here we get his answer.

00:06:57.200 --> 00:06:59.880
This is a really simple thing like, you know, what's the correlation?

00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:01.559
But this is how he did it.

00:07:01.559 --> 00:07:05.359
Now here's how modern researchers, at least the ones who don't use R, might do the same

00:07:05.359 --> 00:07:07.440
thing or handle the same problem.

00:07:07.440 --> 00:07:12.160
They'd say, well, okay, my software gives me these 20 tests to choose from, so I'll

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:16.440
pick this one.

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:21.160
As I said, it is a seductive story, and if the authors of the ASA article are in here,

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:25.079
I apologize, but I don't agree with the explanation.

00:07:25.079 --> 00:07:31.440
And that's largely because I have a PhD in statistics, and if you do statistics completely

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:34.559
correct, you can still have a replication crisis.

00:07:34.559 --> 00:07:37.600
Now when people talk about the replication crisis, they often mention p-values.

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:39.320
Let's use p-values as an example.

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:43.359
People say we're p-hacking, we're misusing p-values, but let's look at what happens when

00:07:43.359 --> 00:07:45.239
you use a p-value correctly.

00:07:45.239 --> 00:07:49.720
A p-value just means that you've done a statistical hypothesis test.

00:07:49.720 --> 00:07:54.799
Almost all statistical tests account for one source of variation, the uncertainty that

00:07:54.799 --> 00:07:57.600
comes from taking a random sample from a population.

00:07:57.600 --> 00:08:01.600
A p-value attempts to quantify the uncertainty.

00:08:01.600 --> 00:08:05.079
But this source of uncertainty is just one source of uncertainty that you will encounter

00:08:05.079 --> 00:08:08.920
every time you try to use data to answer questions about nature.

00:08:08.920 --> 00:08:13.160
This is a graphic developed by my friend and colleague Drew Levy that depicts the other

00:08:13.160 --> 00:08:17.640
sources of unavoidable uncertainty that are involved in the process.

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:23.000
Each small white bullet point here is a different source of uncertainty, but p-values only address

00:08:23.119 --> 00:08:25.359
that one segment over here.

00:08:25.359 --> 00:08:29.959
And those of you who suggest that we should replace p-values with something like a Bayesian

00:08:29.959 --> 00:08:35.559
odds ratio or whatnot need to account for those other sources of uncertainty too.

00:08:35.559 --> 00:08:39.119
A replacement for a p-value isn't going to solve the problem if it also only looks at

00:08:39.119 --> 00:08:41.119
that one source of uncertainty.

00:08:41.119 --> 00:08:48.440
We act as if accounting for that one source of uncertainty justifies the entire process.

00:08:48.440 --> 00:08:56.039
But it doesn't.

00:08:56.039 --> 00:08:57.960
So let me tell you what I think is going on.

00:08:57.960 --> 00:08:59.280
And I could do it with this example.

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:01.960
This is just one of the pages from that Fisher example we were looking at.

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:08.400
If you look closely at this page, you'll see things like formulas, algebraic variables,

00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:09.760
factorial signs.

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:11.640
It looks like math.

00:09:11.640 --> 00:09:13.239
Why might that be a problem?

00:09:13.239 --> 00:09:16.520
Well, let's do a thought experiment.

00:09:16.520 --> 00:09:21.320
Which set of words do you associate with math?

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:26.059
I'm going to guess that's not hypotheses, messy, best guess, or discover, unless you're

00:09:26.059 --> 00:09:34.400
very new to math or very advanced at math.

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:37.599
The beauty of math is that it's so precise.

00:09:37.599 --> 00:09:39.320
It's so logically certain.

00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:41.320
You can prove things with math.

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:43.320
And that's why we love to use it when we can.

00:09:43.320 --> 00:09:46.559
But now think of science, the sort of roll your sleeves up, get your hands dirty and

00:09:46.559 --> 00:09:48.559
make an experiment science.

00:09:48.559 --> 00:09:52.719
You're always working with hypotheses that only represent your best guess.

00:09:52.719 --> 00:09:57.760
At any point in the future, your hypotheses could be revised due to new data or completely

00:09:57.760 --> 00:09:59.000
overturned.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.119
Your only road to glory in science really relies on discovering something that no one

00:10:02.119 --> 00:10:04.820
else has documented yet.

00:10:04.820 --> 00:10:07.599
With science, you cannot prove things.

00:10:07.599 --> 00:10:09.840
These two systems are complementary.

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:13.200
Math as a form of logic can prove things for you, but only things that are already

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:16.640
present in your premises or implied by your definitions.

00:10:16.640 --> 00:10:20.299
Math can't tell you if those definitions could correspond well with reality.

00:10:20.299 --> 00:10:21.299
But science can.

00:10:21.299 --> 00:10:22.679
That's science's job.

00:10:22.679 --> 00:10:26.880
Science helps you pick the most pragmatic definition, and it helps you keep track of

00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:30.880
whether or not that definition corresponds to your current state of knowledge.

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:33.679
But science can never prove that that definition is correct.

00:10:33.679 --> 00:10:37.119
It will always be an estimate or a guess.

00:10:37.119 --> 00:10:40.479
Now those of you who are fans of hypothesis testing might say, well, no, Garrett, you're

00:10:40.479 --> 00:10:41.479
wrong.

00:10:41.479 --> 00:10:43.679
You can prove that a hypothesis is false.

00:10:43.679 --> 00:10:45.359
Well, no.

00:10:45.359 --> 00:10:47.960
You are wrong.

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:52.799
If there is a probability model involved, there will always be some probability, even

00:10:52.799 --> 00:10:58.359
if it's very small, that your hypothesis is correct, no matter what the test says.

00:10:58.359 --> 00:11:02.280
We just round that probability down to zero if it happens to be small, say less than one

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:03.559
in 20.

00:11:03.559 --> 00:11:04.559
And that's the point.

00:11:04.559 --> 00:11:09.960
A statistical hypothesis test looks like math, but it's not math.

00:11:09.960 --> 00:11:13.159
It doesn't deliver logical certainty.

00:11:13.159 --> 00:11:19.679
So we've created a cargo cult by confusing science with math.

00:11:19.679 --> 00:11:23.440
As we started to use more and more data in our science, our methods started to resemble

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:24.799
more and more math.

00:11:24.799 --> 00:11:29.619
Somewhere along the way, as a group of people, we forgot or stopped acting like math was

00:11:29.619 --> 00:11:31.479
only a tool for scientific reasoning.

00:11:31.479 --> 00:11:33.719
We began to believe that our work was like math.

00:11:33.719 --> 00:11:35.840
It could deliver logical proofs.

00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:39.039
Now we must undo that cargo cult, and this is very important because we're on the verge

00:11:39.039 --> 00:11:42.919
of starting a second cargo cult as we use machine learning.

00:11:42.919 --> 00:11:45.960
Our science is starting to look more and more like computer algorithms.

00:11:45.960 --> 00:11:51.039
Computer algorithms are very powerful, automatable, reliable in their own way, but our science

00:11:51.039 --> 00:11:55.479
does not gain those quantities just because we use a computer algorithm.

00:11:55.479 --> 00:12:00.119
And what's worse, when machine learning fails, it seems to fail in a much more public way.

00:12:00.119 --> 00:12:04.599
Does anyone remember this?

00:12:04.599 --> 00:12:09.000
How about this?

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.559
How about the Google photo classification app when that first started?

00:12:13.559 --> 00:12:18.159
These things are not helping the credibility crisis.

00:12:18.159 --> 00:12:20.119
But scientists know what to do.

00:12:20.119 --> 00:12:21.119
It's in your DNA.

00:12:21.119 --> 00:12:24.159
We were taught it all in grade school, and I have a very useful metaphor you could take

00:12:24.159 --> 00:12:28.119
away, and that is the age of exploration when navigators were going out there and discovering

00:12:28.119 --> 00:12:29.119
new continents.

00:12:29.119 --> 00:12:32.760
They were searching for parts of the world that had not yet been observed, and that is

00:12:32.760 --> 00:12:34.640
exactly what scientists do.

00:12:34.640 --> 00:12:36.719
So think of someone like Christopher Columbus.

00:12:36.719 --> 00:12:40.640
He sailed across the sea, he discovered the new world, and he came back to Spain.

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:43.559
Did he offer a logical proof that the new world existed?

00:12:43.559 --> 00:12:45.960
No, that wouldn't make any sense.

00:12:45.960 --> 00:12:49.239
He offered a map, and the map spoke for itself.

00:12:49.239 --> 00:12:54.000
If other explorers followed the map and got to the new world, well, that spoke for itself.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.559
If they followed the map and didn't get to the new world, then that would speak for itself.

00:12:57.559 --> 00:12:59.200
And that's what scientists should do.

00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:04.239
We should create maps of the things we find for other scientists to follow, and then let

00:13:04.239 --> 00:13:08.200
the destination speak for itself when they get there.

00:13:08.200 --> 00:13:12.359
Now scientists are actually pretty good at this, and if you look at the typical scientific

00:13:12.359 --> 00:13:16.000
report, the thing where you start with your hypothesis, you talk about your methods, materials,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.200
and then the results, that is a very good map that goes from the questions you're asking

00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:22.479
to the data that you collect.

00:13:22.479 --> 00:13:28.320
And back in the days when data was almost synonymous with conclusions, that sufficed.

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:32.580
But now in the days of data science, there's a second arc in the journey.

00:13:32.580 --> 00:13:36.520
You have to go from your data to your conclusions, and it's not straightforward.

00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:39.919
You need to provide your fellow scientists a map that can take them along the way that

00:13:39.919 --> 00:13:42.159
you went.

00:13:42.159 --> 00:13:46.440
You can see why this is sort of difficult, because a map that other scientists could

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:49.559
use to reproduce this journey would require some tough things.

00:13:49.559 --> 00:13:50.559
They would need your data.

00:13:51.159 --> 00:13:54.159
They would need the code you use to analyze your data, and they would need the software

00:13:54.159 --> 00:13:59.280
required to run that code, and also they need the reasoning that you use to make every decision

00:13:59.280 --> 00:14:02.840
along the way and to interpret the results at the end.

00:14:02.840 --> 00:14:06.119
It's an impossible-sounding combination of things.

00:14:06.119 --> 00:14:10.960
But this is exactly what R Markdown lets you put in a single report.

00:14:10.960 --> 00:14:15.479
R Markdown is a free R package that provides an authoring format for data science.

00:14:16.320 --> 00:14:22.119
It's a plain text document that allows you to put things there.

00:14:22.119 --> 00:14:26.119
So I don't really have much time to give you a demo, but let me give you a taste of R Markdown.

00:14:26.119 --> 00:14:29.880
This is a story about a scientist named Bill who hasn't updated his headshot in a very

00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:31.880
long time.

00:14:31.880 --> 00:14:35.979
His colleague, Virginia, asks him to solve a problem for their company.

00:14:35.979 --> 00:14:39.719
They work for a brewing factory, and they want to know if the bottling machine is malfunctioning.

00:14:39.719 --> 00:14:44.239
They've heard reports that less than 750 milliliters of beer is being put into each of their bottles,

00:14:44.239 --> 00:14:46.479
so Virginia asks Bill to go check it out.

00:14:46.479 --> 00:14:50.000
He collects some data right off the semi-line, puts it into a spreadsheet, and then he opens

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.880
an R Markdown file, a plain text file.

00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:55.200
He can add code chunks to the file.

00:14:55.200 --> 00:14:58.239
He can run the code chunks as if it were a Jupyter Notebook or something if he wanted

00:14:58.239 --> 00:15:01.719
to see the results in line.

00:15:01.719 --> 00:15:05.840
So this is the graph that he's making here.

00:15:05.840 --> 00:15:11.239
And then he can put text in between the code chunks that explain what he wants to write.

00:15:11.239 --> 00:15:18.039
So he's saying, look, this is what I'm doing, this is the method I'm using.

00:15:18.039 --> 00:15:22.700
And you could even use R code in his text to finish the text form depending on the results

00:15:22.700 --> 00:15:26.280
of his code chunks.

00:15:26.280 --> 00:15:28.320
So he does this.

00:15:28.320 --> 00:15:32.239
The plain text document is very easy to put on GitHub, very easy to diff, see what's changed.

00:15:32.239 --> 00:15:33.239
Not too pretty.

00:15:33.239 --> 00:15:37.359
But the point of R Markdown is that you can then publish results to an impressive format,

00:15:37.359 --> 00:15:38.640
almost any format you like.

00:15:38.640 --> 00:15:42.840
For example, you could use this document, R Markdown will run all the code, use the

00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:47.400
code and the text to make a PDF that you can then pass on to the person you want to impress.

00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:51.000
Or a PowerPoint.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:52.719
Or a book.

00:15:52.719 --> 00:15:53.919
Or a blog post.

00:15:53.919 --> 00:15:54.919
Or a poster.

00:15:54.919 --> 00:15:58.479
UA and other people in the session will be talking about other things you could do with

00:15:58.479 --> 00:16:00.039
R Markdown.

00:16:00.039 --> 00:16:05.440
But everything you need to create the map to make your research reproducible and therefore,

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:09.799
effectively replicable is there in that R Markdown document.

00:16:09.799 --> 00:16:10.799
So that's a taste of R Markdown.

00:16:10.799 --> 00:16:15.200
What I'd like you to do is if you haven't used R Markdown before, try it out, experience

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:17.760
it for yourself, and make your research reproducible.

00:16:17.760 --> 00:16:22.679
Because it's good science, it's good data science, and it's good business.

00:16:22.679 --> 00:16:23.679
Thank you very much.

00:16:23.679 --> 00:16:35.200
We've got time for a couple of questions, and we've got a throwable microphone.

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:44.760
Who has some questions they'd like to ask?

00:16:44.760 --> 00:16:48.719
We've got one question there in the back.

00:16:48.719 --> 00:17:00.200
Oh!

00:17:00.200 --> 00:17:03.559
You play for Cleveland, don't you?

00:17:03.559 --> 00:17:05.920
Okay.

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:08.400
Microphone is working its way back.

00:17:08.400 --> 00:17:10.199
Okay.

00:17:10.199 --> 00:17:12.199
Can you give us your name and ask your question, please?

00:17:12.199 --> 00:17:13.199
Hello?

00:17:13.199 --> 00:17:14.199
Can you hear me?

00:17:14.199 --> 00:17:15.199
I can.

00:17:15.199 --> 00:17:16.199
Sorry, I'm losing my voice a little.

00:17:16.199 --> 00:17:21.599
I just want to ask, is there a functionality in R Markdown to track the potential changes

00:17:21.599 --> 00:17:24.040
in different versions when something changed?

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:26.839
Because what if you can't reproduce the result?

00:17:26.839 --> 00:17:30.800
What if something changed in your data and you get a different set of results?

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:35.680
How is that tracked, being tracked in the R Markdown framework?

00:17:35.680 --> 00:17:41.239
R Markdown itself is just the authoring format, but its existence allows peripheral software

00:17:41.239 --> 00:17:42.939
that can take advantage of this.

00:17:42.939 --> 00:17:46.099
So the obvious one would be any source of version control you could use to track the

00:17:46.099 --> 00:17:47.099
R Markdown.

00:17:47.099 --> 00:17:52.219
But RStudio has developed a publishing platform for R Markdown documents and other documents

00:17:52.219 --> 00:17:56.140
that contain code that can be rerun called RStudio Connect.

00:17:56.140 --> 00:17:59.420
With RStudio Connect, you could publish your R Markdown document and then schedule it to

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:05.459
run on a reoccurring basis to change the parameters right there without having to rewrite code

00:18:05.459 --> 00:18:06.459
and other things.

00:18:06.459 --> 00:18:10.339
You've seen it in Tarif's keynote and maybe other talks around here, too.

00:18:10.339 --> 00:18:14.739
We're putting more and more features into that, and I think tracking is one of those

00:18:14.739 --> 00:18:15.739
features.

00:18:15.739 --> 00:18:16.739
I could be wrong.

00:18:16.739 --> 00:18:19.260
If not, I would expect it to come in the future.

00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:30.420
Until then, in the meantime, you could definitely use Git and other sources of version control.

00:18:30.420 --> 00:18:35.099
What you can keep in your Git repository is the PDF output that contains the results,

00:18:35.099 --> 00:18:37.099
or the HTML output, or whatever your output happens to be.

